<HEAD>Betsy Ross' Descendant Places Wreath</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOY GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Smiling grade school students Monday helped
a descendant of legendary seamstress Betsy Ross place a wreath at
her tomb on the eve of Flag Day.
   Greg Scott of Norristown placed the wreath with the assistance
of Chris Amend and Chris Walsh, both 11 amd from Cranford, N.J.
About 100 people gathered around Mrs. Ross' gravesite in the
Atwater Kent Park for the ceremony. Amend and Walsh were among 62
fifth-graders who attended the ceremony.
   Mrs. Ross, according to some historical accounts, created the
first official American flag, sewing a flag with bars and 13
five-pointed stars. The story goes that a special committee headed
by George Washington visited Mrs. Ross in June 1776 and asked her
to sew a flag based on their rough design.
   Mrs. Ross was the official flagmaker for the Pennsylvania Navy.
But the story of the first stars and stripes has never been
authenticated.
   Scott, an administrator at Bryn Mawr College, plays saxophone in
a big band, and says he is not a practicing Quaker; nor does he
belong to any organizations such as the Sons of the American
Revolution.
   But he said he admires his great-great-great-grandmother, who
died in 1836, because she was a rebel.
   ``I do this because Betsy was a pretty cool old girl,'' Scott
said. ``She was no shrinking violet.''
   Mrs. Ross, born Elizabeth Griscom to Quaker parents on Jan. 1,
1752, broke with the Quaker tradition of pacifism to support the
Revolutionary War, he said.
   The ceremony Monday was preparatory to the city's Flag Day
ceremonies on Tuesday, which commemorates the day Congress
officially adopted the flag in 1777.
</TEXT>
