<TEXT>     Union City throws its second annual Octoberfest today at Kennedy Park to
toast German beer, music, sausages and costumes.;   Ardenwood Historic Farm in
Fremont makes hay out of the day with its fourth annual scarecrow contest
today.;   All the events are free.;   "You could come here and spend a weekend
doing a lot of wild stuff," said Jill Stavosky, who is helping organize Union
City's Octoberfest. "We're telling people to go to everything this weekend
instead of trying to choose. There's a lot going on.";   The Octoberfest --
modeled loosely after the famous event in Munich -- features a half-dozen
types of beer from Winchester Brewing Co. of San Jose and Carlsberg breweries.
A roving German band will play polka, waltz and oompah music. Food booths will
serve sausages and sauerkraut.;   At 1 p.m., revelers can compete in two
costume contests -- one a King Ludwig look-alike contest in honor of an
originator of the famous Munich beer festival, and one to choose the best
German costume.;   There will be booths with crafts, a performance by the
Joanne Brown dancers and commemorative T-shirts and beer mugs.;   Octoberfest
runs from 10 a.m. to 4 p.m. today only at the park, 1333 Decoto Road.;   A few
miles away, Newark will mark the beginning of the monarch butterfly migration
season with the Monarch Festival from 10 a.m. to 6 p.m. both days at Jarvis
Avenue and Newark Boulevard in front of the Newark Marketplace shopping
center.;   It features crafts, food booths, entertainment, horse and buggy
rides -- and maybe even some butterfly sightings. It also offers appearances
by "Monarch Man," a park employee who dresses in a butterfly costume and talks
to children about the graceful flutterers. He'll show up about 11 a.m. and
again in the afternoon.;   Real monarchs are known to stop each migrating
season at a large eucalyptus grove, which is now split by the freeway and the
shopping center, providing ample reason to celebrate, said Marilyn Prows of
the Newark Chamber of Commerce.;   And in Fremont, Ardenwood Historic Farm and
the J.B. Perry Farms will host the Ardenwood Scarecrow Contest at 10 a.m.
today. In that event, public and private preschools and elementary schools
compete to see who can build the best figure of hay. Each scarecrow must
represent a famous person in history.;   Last year, winning scarecrows
included depictions of Martha Washington, a pilgrim couple, Betsy Ross,
Sitting Bull and Marie Antoinette.;   The winning schools get prizes,
including field trips. And the scarecrows will stand amid the cornstalks until
Nov. 1.  </TEXT>
