<HEAD>Supreme Court Decision Revives Flag Day</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Two huge flags were being unfurled in New York City and tiny
banners were being planted on lawns in a Minnesota town for Flag
Day today _ a practically forgotten holiday until the Supreme Court
helped stir affection for Old Glory.
   Shopkeepers reported flag sales are up as well since the high
court on Monday struck down a federal law against flag burning. The
ruling has spurred the drive for a constitutional amendment against
desecrating the flag.
   In Philadelphia, 14-year-old Katie Appelget was to read her
winning essay in the annual ``What the Flag Means'' contest. The
ceremony was sponsored by the museum and home of Betsy Ross, who
legend has it made the first Stars and Stripes.
   ``The American flag unites us all,'' wrote Katie. ``Even though
we may speak different dialects or come from different backgrounds,
we share one common element, the American flag.''
   Two 20-by-30-foot flags were to be hoisted today at the site of
the 1964 World's Fair in New York City, the first time flags of
that size have been flown since the fair.
   Later in the day, 100 newly arrived Soviet Jews were to be given
American flags and a boat ride past Ellis Island and the Statue of
Liberty, courtesy of a tourist boat company and the New York
Association for New Americans.
   In Northfield, Minn., some 25 workers at a realty planned to
place 3,000 plastic flags on residents' lawns. Broker Millie Berg
said city officials and police have given the go-ahead, but
flag-planters will skip the homes of two people who complained.
   Not everyone in the town of 10,000 was happy with the
``intrusive political statement,'' as resident Gloria Stier put it.
   In Omaha, Neb., merchants said flag sales have been booming
since the Supreme Court ruling.
   ``A lot of it has to do with the flag controversy,'' Paul
Cullen, sales manager at Cosgrave Church Goods, said Tuesday.
   Cullen said the store sold 40 flags in two days this week,
compared to just five on an average day. Although sales increase
around Memorial Day and the Fourth of July, he said, customers
usually forget about Flag Day.
   Buyers this year seem to be ``making a statement'' by buying
flags for Flag Day, said Dave Anderson, owner of Anderson Catholic
Supplies.
</TEXT>
