<HEAD>Singing Sheep Headed For Success</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In an attempt to prove that anything can become a
pop hit, two Englishmen have released a dance version of Baa Baa
Black Sheep sung _ or rather bleated _ by Betsy the sheep.
   Five hundred copies of the single by Mark Richards and Ian
Fletcher have been on sale since Monday for about $2 in central
England record stores.
   Aileen Cameron, the secretary at Image Television where Richards
and Fletcher work, described the office as chaotic with requests
for records, photos of Betsy and interviews.
   Richards, who works as a scriptwriter when not acting as Betsy's
manager, said three radio stations have added the song to their
playlists. He said he and Fletcher would also welcome bids to
produce a music video.
   The sounds of the new Baa Baa Black Sheep song filled the Oasis
record store in Derby, 135 miles north of London, which has been
playing it regularly. Sales clerk Tricia Nicholls said Wednesday a
few party disc jockeys had expressed interest but so far, only one
of six copies has been sold.
   The producers said they were surprised by the amount of interest
in their song, which started out as a joke to poke fun at the music
industry's increasing use of electronic mixing.
   ``The Betsy Boogie starts out on hands and knees and then you
chew some grass like a sheep would do,'' Richards explained in an
interview.
   Fletcher told Sky Television: ``It's got certain influences of
some of the songs that are on the charts at the moment. I think we
wanted to prove just how little effort needs to go into making
something to get it into the charts nowadays.''
   Betsy's next hit, Richards said, will be a re-mix of the Beach
Boys' song, Baa Baa Barbara Ann.
</TEXT>
