<HEAD>Standard-Bearers Still Unknown, But Work On President's Flag
Continues</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats and Republicans have yet to
nominate their parties' standard-bearers this November, but 15
modern-day Betsy Rosses are embroidering the flags that will
accompany the new president who will take office next January.
   In the basement of Building 13 of the Defense Department's
supply center, below the gymnasium-sized rooms where huge spools of
olive drab thread turn into acres of U.S. Army fatigues, the women
of the embroidering room serve the next president with needles in
hand and thimbles on fingers.
   Beyond the whine of sewing machines, behind the cinder block
walls, the basement of Building 13 is the only place in the country
where the president's flags are made.
   Tiny spots of chalk dust outline the eagle and stars that make
up the president's coat of arms, as the women gently poke 19 colors
of silk and synthetic threads through the navy blue rayon banner,
held taut across a wooden rack.
   For the women in the embroidery room, who spend most of their
time embroidering detail on military units' flags, the opportunity
to work on a flag for the president holds a special thrill.
   ``When he talks on television, I look at the seal,'' said Maria
T. Negron, who learned embroidery as a hobby while growing up in
Puerto Rico.
   The women embroider hundreds of flags each year for various
military units, Cabinet members and Congress, but the presidential
flag is most important, the workers said.
   ``We make sure all the employees get a chance to work on a
presidential flag. It's one of the best morale builders,'' said
Frank Bennett, production chief at the center's manufacturing
directorate.
   One worker can embroider both sides of a 4-foot, 4-inch by
5-foot, 6-inch presidential flag in nine weeks, Bennett said.
However, if a deadline is looming, two or more women will embroider
the same flag, he said.
   Two or three flags are made for the president in most years, but
with a new president taking office, seven new flags are being
created.
   ``This flag symbolizes the most powerful office in the world.
And wherever he goes, the flag goes with him,'' Bennett said.
   At least five are always in use: one at the Oval Office, one
aboard Air Force One, one at the White House portico for outdoor
speeches and receptions for heads of state, one with the
president's honor guard, and one as backup, said Col. Victor M.
Hernandez, chief of the manufacturing directorate at the supply
center.
   Laden with symbolism, the coat of arms features an American
eagle clasping an olive branch in one talon and a bundle of 13
arrows in the other. A constellation of 13 stars runs through a
series of rays coming from the eagle's shoulders. The rays shoot
through an arc of thirteen cloud puffs.
   The coat of arms also appears on the president's seal, which is
most often seen attached to the front of a lectern.
   The embroidery room is staffed by middle-aged women who
recognize that few members of the younger generation are interested
in hand embroidery.
   ``Both sides have to be the same. No machine can ever do that,''
said Connnie Martins, who brought her skill to Philadelphia from
Portugal about 18 years ago. ``My daughter, she doesn't like it.''
   Each stitch is matched on each side of the flag, so the eagle
looking to his right on one side is looking to its left on the
other. The only part that doesn't appear backward on the flag's
opposite side are the words ``E Pluribus Unum,'' Latin for ``out of
many, one.''
   When the embroidery is finished, a synthetic gold-tone fringe is
stitched to three sides of the flag.
