<DESCRIPT>  SAN-JOSE; FAMILY; HOUSING; HISTORY; BUILDING; REPAIR; AWARD  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  IN A classic "Ugly Duckling" scenario, a San Jose Victorian has gone from
being "the worst house on the block" to being the sole West Coast winner of a
National Trust for Historic Preservation award.;    "We were excited and
pleased they picked a house that two ordinary homeowners had done," says Betsy
Mathieson of the Great American Home Award she and her husband, Scott, won for
their 10-year residential restoration project. "This is our first house, our
first renovation, our first woodworking, our first wiring -- it's our first
everything."  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Home  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  LOVE'S LABOR'S WON
COUPLE'S 10-YEAR RESTORATION EFFORT BEARS
FRUIT  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  See also related stoies on pages 2-3D of this section.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Bruce Judd, an architect with Architectural Resources Group in San
Francisco and one of the judges of the competition, recalls being "impressed"
by the Mathiesons' efforts.;    "It's not a grand house or a major piece of
architecture, but it's a nice, smaller, more typical kind of house. These
people had lovingly researched what was there and tried to put it back. They
had a long-range plan and executed it very well," says Judd, who has served on
the six-panel judging committee since the award program started two years
ago.;    "We saw a lot of projects where developers went in and in two years
spent a lot of money, but you could tell there wasn't the love and affection
in the process that the Mathiesons had," he adds.;    Scott and Betsy
Mathieson, both engineering geologists, purchased their single story,
1,170-square-foot Queen Anne cottage in 1979 for $53,500.;    "We wanted a
Victorian and after looking in San Francisco, Alameda, West Oakland and San
Jose, we could afford San Jose," says 36-year-old Scott.;    "We wanted a
neighborhood that was mostly Victorians that we believed would improve rather
than deteriorate. We couldn't afford a fixed-up house, but we needed one in
good enough shape to live in while we restored it," says 35-year-old Betsy.;  
 The house the Mathiesons chose is on Pierce Avenue -- a block-long street
bounded by Almaden Avenue and Market Street, just three blocks from the San
Jose Convention Center.;    While some homeowners might shudder at the notion
of a convention center going up in their neighborhood, the Mathiesons are
philosophical about it.;    "The convention center helped us because we
organized the neighborhood to keep from getting run over," says Scott of the
Market/Almaden Neighborhood Association. The group lobbied for new trees and
old-fashioned streetlights in the area and has been successful in keeping a
condominium project on Pierce Avenue compatible with neighborhood
architecture.;    The Mathiesons' restoration project is a familiar one to
lovers of old houses.;    Among the joys was the discovery of Maude Lawler's
childish signature on a section of living room plaster. Research revealed
"Mrs. Annie C. Lawler, a dressmaker" lived in the house in 1892. The
Mathiesons preserved the signature and show it to visitors.;     Seeking the
right doorknobs;    Preservation was a key objective of the Mathiesons, who
opted for restoration over replacement whenever possible. Still searching for
the exact pattern doorknobs that match the few original ones in their home,
Betsy recognized one on another Victorian home while doing some political
canvassing. She's asked the owner if he would be willing to trade it for a
different pattern from the same era.;    On the down side, "the house had
lowered ceilings, sleeping lofts had been put in some rooms, the bathroom had
been modernized and had a leaking shower stall and the roof had been leaking
for years, creating soft spots in the ceilings," Scott says. Floors were as
much as six inches out of level and wood paneling had been used to camouflage
crooked portions of walls.;    The roof was a first priority, taking the
Mathiesons a week to pull off seemingly endless layers of redwood shingles and
roofing materials. After three more weeks' work they had a new roof of cedar
shingles, and Betsy used a saber saw to reproduce the original fish scale
shingles over the front bay window.;    Plaster was repaired, only to later be
damaged when the house had to be raised to replace the mud sill foundation
with a new reinforced concrete foundation and full basement.;     4 weeks 'in
the air';    Scrapbooks filled with photos are reminders of the nine months
the Mathiesons lived with a basement kitchen, using only a microwave and a
toaster oven for cooking; the four weeks they spent "up in the air" while the
house was raised to build the new foundation; and the three summers Betsy
spent stripping exterior paint with a heat gun.;    "We did everything in the
wrong order," Betsy says. "Now we know how to do it right -- now we'd do the
roof and foundation and then rip out the plaster and put in the new wiring and
plumbing.";    In spite of discouraging setbacks, the Mathiesons persevered.
"We worked on weekends, but not always. We went extremely slowly, but we
learned the right way," Betsy says.;    The exterior of the home was painted
olive brown with gold, cream and dark red trim in 1988. From January 1985
until August 1989 they lived with the interior sheetrocked walls painted a
flat white. It was the 100th anniversary of the sewer permit issued for their
home Dec. 10, 1889, combined with a Victorian Preservation Association house
tour, that caused the Mathiesons to finally push the project.;    "The last
three months of 1989 we worked full time, 20 hours a day," Scott says.;   
"The house tour was an impetus to finish," Betsy says.;    In that brief time
an expert wood grainer, Zane Working of Oakland, matched original walnut and
oak graining on doors, wainscoting, trim and windows. He also touched up the
faux tortoise shell finish on the cast-iron fireplace front in the dining
room.;    All seven rooms of the house are finished with hand-printed
Victorian-style wallpapers from Bradbury &amp; Bradbury Wallpapers in Benicia. The
ceiling of the dining room alone has 150 individually cut pieces of paper
forming the elaborate patterns.;    The Mathieson home is furnished with
family heirloom furniture and paintings as well as antique pieces they've
found in travels throughout Northern California. One particularly impressive
piece is an Eastlake Murphy Bed marked with a Feb. 3, 1883, date and a San
Francisco address.;    The Mathiesons are proud that by salvaging and careful
shopping they were able to remodel the kitchen for about $1,000, including
replacing cabinets and installing a vintage Wedgwood stove.;    Ten days
before the Oct. 28, 1989, house tour the Loma Prieta earthquake hit. "The
brick chimneys next door fell, but we had no damage," Scott says, adding that
he had re-plumbed the bathroom just five days earlier.;    Many couples
consider one renovation to be enough, and in some cases even one too many. Not
the Mathiesons, who both claim they would do it again.;    "Eventually we'd
like to own a bigger house, a Queen Anne with a two-story tower," Betsy says.
In the meantime, they are awaiting the birth of their first child this summer.  </TEXT>
