<DESCRIPT>  OPINION; US; IMAGE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  O say can you see,; Through the tar spreader's fumes,  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Editorial  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  RAISING THE STARS AND STRIPES TO HIGH TACKINESS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Commentary
Joanne Jacobs, who writes a column on Mondays and Thursdays, is a member of
the Mercury News editorial pages staff.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>  What so proudly we hailed; On the Buick's antenna?; Whose broad stripes and
bright stars; Through the fog and the night,; O'er the 4 x 4's cab; Was so
gallantly streaming.; Seen at Orchard Hardware,; In a fireman's dyed hair,
Dresses, jackets and socks,; Yes, our flag's everywhere . . .;    O say does
that star-spangled banner yet wave . . . ?;    You bet it does, but I don't
think the flag-wavers are doing much honor to the flag these days.;    Does it
honor the flag when it is flown from a road-making machine, or whipped by the
wind as a car drives down the freeway at 70 mph, or -- as I saw one the other
day -- tied to the toolbox of a pick-up truck? I guess it was tied so it
wouldn't blow away, but it was being treated like a rag, not a flag.;    Union
City Fire Department decided that yellow ribbons were OK, to show support for
the troops, but flag emblems, presumably carrying a more controversial
message, had to be removed from helmets, fire engines and other departmental
property.;    So a fire captain had a red, white and blue flag shaved and dyed
into his hair.;    Well, it's the home of the free, all right. And, I guess,
the land of the brave too. But what does it prove to display a cloth, plastic,
paper or scalp-sculpted flag?;    The flag can mean any number of things these
days, from hoping our men and women in uniform come home safely to hoping they
come home safely and victoriously. It can say: USA rules. Or: Hey, this is my
country too and I don't like the way the First Ass-Kicker is running it.;   
As Burger King says: Have it your way.;    Support-the-president marchers
carry American flags. End-the-war marchers carry American flags.;    People
flying flags at their homes are reporting their flags stolen. Apparently,
thieves are pro-flag these days.;    Fundamentally, the flag symbolizes
nationhood, "the conviction that this country is superior to all other
countries because you were born in it," as George Bernard Shaw said. Or as the
Beach Boys sang: "Be true to your school. Just like you would to your girl."; 
  KGO talkhawk Jim Eason got a bunch of Mercury News readers to cancel their
subscriptions because our editors refused to dump all those boring words and
print a full-page flag, so people who were too cheap to go out and buy a flag
and too honest or cowardly to steal one could cut it out and put it in the
window. (Why doesn't Eason stop talking and devote his show to playing the
Star-Spangled Banner?);    This is dumb patriotism. I don't mean "dumb" as in
stupid, though it can be, but in the classic sense: lacking the power of
words. Words can define which national ideals the flag-waver favors: land of
the free, home of the brave, Bill of Rights, Marine Corps Hymn, etc.;    When
readers called to ask, "Why are you against the flag?" they started by saying
that printing the flag simply means "we're Americans" but then said the flag
means "we support the troops" and "we support the president" and "we hate
Saddam Hussein.";    When the newspaper reports on the war or takes an
editorial position on the war, we're supposed to say a lot more than that, and
say it a lot more clearly. And we're supposed to stand or fall on our own
credibility, without sponsorship by the stars and stripes. The newspaper may
be fishwrap but it shouldn't be flagwrapped.;    I read a story the other day
about the failure of diplomacy to prevent the war that had a line about flags
hanging limp and dispirited on Embassy Row. It was a pretty pathetic fallacy:
If it had been a windy day, the flags would have been streaming in the breeze,
war or no war.;    This is dumb in the colloquial sense. Flags don't mourn
diplomatic stalemate or cheer military victory. Flags don't think or talk.
Flags mean what people want them to mean, and if they're used too casually
they don't mean anything at all.;    The New York Times fashion section
reported Feb. 11 that flagwear is absolutely the latest thing, observing:
"Wearing depictions of the American flag was considered disrespectful. That
taboo died with the onset of the Woodstock generation. There are now flags on
T-shirts and sweatshirts, on swimsuits and beach towels, on tote bags and
umbrellas.";    Also: $500 bomber jackets, pillows, baseball caps, socks,
wallets, nightshirts, loungewear, jeans, boxer shorts and barrettes. Macy's
sells a $1,600 jeweled flag minaudiere. I don't even know what a minaudiere
is. (Actually, I looked it up, so I know now. It's a small woman's handbag
used for formal wear.);    The Woodstock generation wore flag shirts or
flag-bottomed jeans to show disrespect for the traditions of their elders.
Perhaps I spent too long in Girl Scouts, but I fail to see how it shows
patriotism or honors the flag to wear a stretch tank dress with a starry
breast and a stripey side ($60), or a cotton canvas jacket ($230) that looks
like Betsy Ross turned her surplus stock into ready-to-wear.;    Burning the
flag shows more respect. The flag-burner implicitly recognizes the flag's
symbolism as he symbolically rejects it. The guy who wears the flag on his
socks or his boxers equates it with an Izod alligator or a Lauren polo pony.
It's just the fashionable designer emblem of the season, like Scud jewelry in
Amman.;    Our flag is being used -- to make a political statement, to make a
fashion statement, to make money -- to make patriotism as simple as wearing a
T-shirt.;    I own a flag and I fly it on traditional flag-flying holidays.
These days, I show my respect for the flag by leaving it alone.  </TEXT>
