<LEADPARA>  The star of such films as The Breakfast Club, WarGames, Betsy's Wedding and
Only the Lonely, Sheedy, 29, lives in Los Angeles and New York.; Q. Ally is
short for Alexandra. Does anyone call you Alexandra?  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  West  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  ALLY SHEEDY  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  WEST CLOSE-UPS
INTERVIEW  </MEMO>
<TEXT>  A. My mom calls me Alex.; Q. You've spoken and written quite a bit about your
mother, Charlotte Sheedy.; A. Both of my parents are really high achievers. My
mother was born in a very poor family, the only Jewish family in the black
section of Philadelphia, so they were, like, outcasts. She didn't graduate
from high school; she was illiterate and out on her own at 16, and today she
owns the Charlotte Sheedy Literary Agency in New York City.;    Q. Didn't she
try to steer you away from acting when you were a teen-ager?;    A. No, but
when I was acting in plays in New York, when I was 15, she hung up on someone
who called offering to help me get work in TV commercials. But she's really
honest: She told me she did it, and I called the woman back. Eventually I was
offered some commercials, and my mom and I had a fight about whether I should
take them.;    Q. Was your early success a heady experience for you -- getting
money and fame as a teen-ager?;    A. No, high achievement was the way I was
brought up. What I didn't expect was how a lot of people are put off if you're
successful. I wasn't prepared for the envy. It's still difficult. It's
difficult for me to make friends. And dating is hard sometimes; I don't always
know if the man is interested in me. And if you get involved with someone
who's prominent in his own right, that can be complicated. The only one of
those relationships that has worked for years and years is Paul Newman and
Joanne Woodward. I think the Demi Moore-Bruce Willis marriage will last.;   
Q. In 1985 you were in The Breakfast Club. I've heard of people who have seen
that film 30 or 40 times.;    A. It's a real cult favorite. I think it was so
popular because it expresses some emotional experiences that are pretty
universal. My character, Allison, has this scene -- she had been covering
herself up with makeup -- and she goes off with a friend and they take all
that stuff off, and she begins to see and reveal who she really is.;    Q. The
Breakfast Club and St. Elmo's Fire, which you were also in, seem to fit
together, with many of the same actors doing a lot of soul-searching. Any
chance for a new movie that will follow up on the characters as they head into
their 30s?;    A. No, I don't think so. It would be so hard to get everyone
together. We're all over the place. I've kept in touch with that group. The
person I'm closest to is Demi Moore.;    Q. Has it been difficult for you to
make the transition from adolescent to adult roles?;    A. It has, I think
because I look a lot younger than my age. Sometimes I get turned down for
parts I want because "you're too young, you're too young." I still get sent
younger roles but I would rather work less and grow up. So I do one thing a
year. My part last summer in Betsy's Wedding was a breakthrough to adult parts
for me, playing this adult woman -- an adult woman who can't get a date!;   
Q. Didn't you buy rights to the book about rock 'n' roll groupies, I'm With
the Band, in hopes of developing a good role for yourself?;    A. Yes, but no
one wants to make that into a movie! I would hear from studio executives, "We
can't make a woman groupie into a sympathetic character." I think it would be
a terrific film if someone wonderful like Robert Altman wanted to do it and
focus on this really interesting woman and the whole '60s scene; it's not just
about some dead rock star. But it just hasn't happened. I give up.;    Q. In
your recent book of poetry, Yesterday I Saw the Sun, you write about some dark
times you've been through with addictions. You went to Hazelden, the
detox/rehab center?;    A. Yes. Those addictions and compulsive behaviors are
-- they're extremely powerful. I have great respect for them. It's something I
need to be aware of every day. Poetry helps me make sense of it all. I'm very
thankful I'm able to express myself with words. The poetry collection is my
second book, actually. I published She Was Nice to Mice when I was 12.;    Q.
One of your poems has a nice line about Hollywood: "driving down Sunset
Boulevard/her friends' faces/stare at her/from billboards.";    A. Those
billboards with 40-foot-tall faces, yes, it's a very, very strange feeling to
see your friends up there; there's no connection between that and the person
you know. It's even weirder when it's your own face. It's exciting; and also a
little bit unnerving. It made me nuts -- "Oh my God, now I have to live up to
this."  </TEXT>
