<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<DATELINE> NEW YORK  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eloise Lipscomb is like a kid in a toy store. 
Come to think of it, Eloise Lipscomb, though 25, is a kid in a toy store. 
As one of two personal shoppers at F.A.O. Schwarz, she escorts the rich, the sometimes famous and the frequently confused through 37,000 square feet of things that talk, glow, roar, rev and go beep in the night. 
And she is fully capable of having a spirited, even meaningful discussion with a barking, whimpering puppet dog or with a bear whose ursine gibberish generally makes sense only to a highly imaginative child. 

   "I definitely have a child's mind," says Ms. Lipscomb. 
She'd better. 
Many department stores have personal shoppers, but they tend to be generalists. 
Ms. Lipscomb has been a Schwarz personal shopper for three years, specializing, as the store does, only in toys. 
It's gotten to the point where she takes her work home with her. 
Her Greenwich Village apartment houses an antique teeter-totter used as a coffee table, a baby doll, two pull toys, a train set and several teddy bears. 

   "I know exactly why kids like things right away," she says. 
"I have a very good memory of my childhood. 
I remember what I liked at a lot of different ages." 
Being named Eloise also adds to Ms. Lipscomb's professional credibility. 
Some of the store's young patrons are convinced she's Kay Thompson's heroine grown up and on loan from the Plaza Hotel just across Fifth Avenue. 

   And like the original Eloise, Ms. Lipscomb is ready to tell grown-ups what to do. 
When a client announces that he's shopping for a three-year-old boy, count on Ms. Lipscomb to plump for a wooden train that connects with magnets. 
For a five year old, she advises the aforementioned vociferous puppet dog. 

   "Ten," confides Ms. Lipscomb, "is a tricky time because if you give kids immature toys they feel like they're being treated like a baby, but they still like toys. 
I can tell people exactly how a 10 year old is going to react to things." (A 10 year old, she believes, will react badly to the offer of a child doll. 
Better to go with an adult doll, a telescope or a chemistry set.) 

   If she's working with a new client, Ms. Lipscomb will ask the child's age, gender and favored activities. 
"As I start walking people around the store and telling them about the different products it becomes clear what their children like. 
I never ask how much they want to spend, but it becomes evident very quickly." 

   Certain clients like grandfather and chicken king Frank Perdue refuse to tour the sales floor and will simply bring in a shopping list. 
"I think it's better to walk the store because it definitely increases the sale," says Ms. Lipscomb. 

   Over the Christmas season she will average three or four customers a day, both walk-ins and appointments. 
Her Museum of Modern Art calendar is laced with names such as Gayfryd Steinberg, the wife of financier Saul Steinberg; the Steinbergs' two-year-old daughter, Holden (who brings her nanny); Richard Thomas; Michael Jackson (who generally comes disguised in a wig, a mask or a mustache); Christie Brinkley; Whoopi Goldberg; Betsy Bloomingdale; Diana Ross; and Katharine Graham. 

   Being rich and famous is not, however, a prerequisite for the privilege of walking the floor with Ms. Lipscomb, although most of her 100 regular clients think nothing of running up a $2,000-plus tab at Christmas. 
"A personal shopper sale of $1,000 is no big deal," says Ms. Lipscomb, who in Imelda Marcos's palmier days sold her a "toy" red Mercedes for $7,500. 
"You start getting impressed around $5,000." 

   "But if people want a personal shopper and they want to spend $20, they want to spend $10, it's okay," says the store's general manager, Cathy Windt. 
"If they spend $5, if they spend $5,000 we offer them the same service." 

   That service can include a walk-through on a Sunday morning before official store hours, as it did recently for Schlumberger heiress and fashion designer Christophe de Menil, her daughter Taya Snow, Taya's three children, Caroline, Dash and Max, two nannies and a family friend. 

   "I want the clock," whispers two-year-old Max staring in awe at the two-story F.A.O. Schwarz symbol dominating the entrance to the store. 

   "Why does Dash want Inhumanoids for Christmas?" his mother wants to know in some distress. 

   "Because they're ugly," says Ms. Lipscomb with the resigned air of someone who knows better than to argue with a five year old. 

   "I want a trillion of them," says Dash, now busy with the remote-control cars. 

   "Does your daughter need Barbie accessories?" asks Ms. Lipscomb, who knows from previous outings with the de Menils that Caroline already has Barbie's car, hot tub and horse and trailer. 

   "She should have the vanity, some new Barbie clothes, and she needs some more Barbies," says Ms. Snow. 
"Maybe the Peruvian and Greek Barbie and Rocker Barbie. 
Maybe I'll get two Rocker Barbies. 
But I don't know if we want the Barbie workout center." 

   "Do you like dolls, Caroline?" asks Mrs. de Menil, busily adding to her shopping list as the group stops at the Raggedy Ann display. 
"Dash likes to make things. 
But we haven't gotten to his department yet." 

   "Read off that list. 
I want to take off all the outrageous things," murmured Ms. Snow as soon as her indulgent mother was out of earshot. 

   "I want the clock," whispers Max as the de Menils make a hurried exit a few minutes after the store opens at noon, leaving behind a formidable list of stuffed animals, blocks, dolls, doll clothes, cars, castles, Jungle Gyms, books and puppets totaling $3,000 to $4,000 -- and they'll be back. 

   "The de Menils are wonderful because they know what they want," says Ms. Lipscomb. 
"People who can't make up their minds are the hardest part of the job. 
I don't like to push things down their throats but I get impatient with 'I don't know.'" 

   Ms. Lipscomb also gets impatient with parents who want to push their offspring into toys that are beyond them -- for example, a computer for a newborn or a train for a six month old. 
"They'll say 'my child is only three but she's a genius and I know she's ready for this six-year-old educational toy.' 

   "Parents are worse offenders than grandparents," Ms. Lipscomb says. 
"Grandparents are objective when they should be. 

   "I'm really compulsive," says Ms. Lipscomb, who lives by two abiding rules: 1. 
Test the toy. 2. 
Include batteries. 
"Last year, a customer bought three remote-control cars for his kids and I forgot to enclose batteries. 
So I hand delivered them with an apologetic note." 

   Right now, however, batteries are the least of her concerns. 
"I have one customer who has 11 children and comes in and does a separate personal shop for each one," she sighs. 
"He just spent $1,500 on his 11-year-old daughter. 
And he has 10 kids to go." 

   ---
   Ms. Kaufman is a free-lance writer based in New York. 

</TEXT>
