<HL> RJR Wants to Leave Winston-Salem, N.C., for Atlanta
---
Move Reflects Nabisco Brands'
Increasing Influence Over Its Parent
---
By Betsy Morris
Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL>
<DD> 01/12/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> RJR FW
FOOD &amp; BEVERAGE, HOUSEHOLD GOODS, SUPERMARKETS, TOBACCO (FAB) </IN>
<DATELINE> ATLANTA  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Winston-Salem, N.C., without R.J. Reynolds would be like Hershey, Pa., without Hershey, or Detroit without General Motors. 
Unthinkable. 

   But if any doubt remains that tobacco no longer dominates RJR Nabisco Inc., it will be erased this week when the company unveils a proposal once considered sacrilege: moving the corporate headquarters to Atlanta. 

   The management is expected to propose the shift south to its board Thursday, according to sources close to RJR. 
It has been looking for office space in Atlanta and would move 300 of its current 1,000-member headquarter staff there, the sources said. 
About 200 to 500 employees will be laid off, according to varying accounts from RJR executives, with the remainder reassigned to R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co. in Winston-Salem and other operating units. 

   RJR will continue to maintain two major tobacco plants and more than 13,000 employees in Winston-Salem. 

   Nevertheless, the move is a bold first strike by F. Ross Johnson, the former Nabisco chief executive officer who became RJR's new chief only 12 days ago. 
It signals that under Mr. Johnson, RJR will no longer be tied to its staid tobacco heritage. 

   The proposal also confirms rampant fears in Winston-Salem that while it was RJR that paid $4.9 billion to acquire Nabisco Brands Inc. in 1985, it is Nabisco that has truly taken over. 

   "The word 'Reynolds' and Winston-Salem are more or less synonymous," said Wayne A. Corpening, the city's mayor, responding to press reports of RJR moving plans. 
"I didn't sleep much last night," Mr. Corpening added. 

   For Winston-Salem, with a 1980 population of 132,000, the loss of RJR is the loss of a resident corporate patron saint. 
Through much of the last century, RJR has hired entire families, and provided them with low-cost housing, day care, even band concerts and baseball games. 

   It was RJR, or its founders, who helped give Winston-Salem a center for the arts, influenced Wake Forest University to come to the city and raised a building so striking -- the tobacco company's headquarters built in 1929 -- it served as a model for New York's famed Empire State Building. 

   But the announcement last August that Mr. Johnson would succeed J. Tylee Wilson as chief executive was handwriting on the wall for many Winston-Salem residents. 
Since then, several top RJR posts have been filled with Mr. Johnson's top aides from Nabisco and RJR employees let go. 
Rumors had it that RJR would move its headquarters either to New York or the East Hanover, N.J., headquarters of its Nabisco Brands Inc. unit. 

   But as recently as late last week, the company denied it would leave Winston-Salem, insisting that Mr. Johnson had bought a house there and that he had even plunged into civic activities, such as heading up a major fund-raising effort for the North Carolina Zoological Society. 
Now an RJR spokesman refuses to confirm or deny the proposed move to Atlanta. 

   Though seemingly a bolt from the blue, a move to Atlanta makes sense for RJR. Atlanta's airport is much more accessible than Winston-Salem for travel from offices in New York and New Jersey and RJR's extensive overseas operations. 

   Moreover, bustling, cosmopolitan Atlanta is a much more suitable home for Mr. Johnson, a hard-driving, hard-playing executive who thrives on late-night business meetings, glitzy golf tournaments, and famous friends, the likes of which include athletes Frank Gifford, Bobby Orr, and the Canadian Prime Minister, Brian Mulroney. 

   The move also makes sense for a paternalistic, old-fashioned company that has had trouble making the bloody break with its tradition. 
Although the company has been placing substantial investments outside of tobacco for 10 years now, it has continued to retain the image of "a tobacco company with other interests," says an executive. 
Although Mr. Johnson's predecessor Mr. Wilson boldly bought businesses and sold them -- including Kentucky Fried Chicken and Canada Dry -- his management was slow to cut the umbilical cord to Winston-Salem. 
Mr. Wilson remains chairman until next year. 

   Bringing the company to Atlanta would drive home Mr. Johnson's new strategy, which is to refit RJR with a more modern holding company structure, using a lean headquarters staff to provide limited support to four major, highly autonomous operating units. 
RJR has a total of 130,000 employees world-wide. 

   Tobacco will continue to be a major business, in addition to the food and liquor businesses. 
Tobacco contributes roughly 40% of sales and 64% of earnings. 
RJR had third-quarter net income of $750 million, or $2.62 a share, on sales of $14 billion. 

   In recent months, management has been reviewing the headquarters jobs, with an eye toward sharply trimming staff. 
When the process is completed in March, the headquarters will be trimmed to about 300 employees, who would move to Atlanta. 
While that number isn't so huge, RJR would become the biggest corporation headquartered in Atlanta, whose corporate landscape is now dominated by Coca-Cola Co. 

   The possible move also fuels speculation that First Wachovia Corp., a combination of First Atlanta Corp. and Wachovia Corp., of Winston-Salem, would also shift headquarters to Atlanta. 
Currently the bank holding company has headquarters in both cities. 
Atlanta's hyperactive commercial real estate community is said to be licking its chops over both prospects. 

