</SO>
<LP>
   It seems like only yesterday that the mother of all child
sex abuse circuses -- the McMartin Preschool trial in
California ended with the prosecution thoroughly routed. The
McMartin jurors acquitted the defendants on the ground that
the charges put before them were, to say the least, not
credible. The verdict ended years of nightmares for the
defendants, but could hardly undo the emotional and financial
ruin inflicted over five years of a lurid investigation and
trial. When the preposterousness of the prosecutors' charges
and evidence, the techniques of the state's child therapists
(who put the abuse charges into childrens' mouths) all stood
revealed, it was said that the lesson of the McMartin case
would prevent such cruel fiascos from recurring. But as the
remarkable two-hour "Frontline" film by Ofra Bikel titled
"Innocence Lost" reveals (9-11 p.m. EDT tomorrow, on PBS), we
are about to see McMartin II take place in Edenton, N.C. The
program covers the investigations and the pre-trial hearings.
The actual trial will begin early in June.
   This time the people caught up in charges of child sex
abuse are the owners and teachers of the Little Rascals
nursery school. Edenton is, as its name suggests, an idyllic
setting, steeped in colonial history. In this green and
pleasant place, the child sex abuse fever has struck with a
vengeance, as it has in other towns in the nation where, in
the last decade, a single anonymous accusation has been
enough to set off an investigation, leading to charges
rapidly multiplying into the hundreds, and extending to an
ever wider circle of people accused -- usually nursery school
teachers or other child care workers.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In Edenton, what began with one child soon progressed to a
point where prosecutors were claiming 90 children had been
abused. That the filmmakers deliver this anatomy of a child
abuse prosecution with calm even-handedness makes the story
they tell no less chilling. For this is, make no mistake, an
indictment -- and not of the defendants. It is a memorable
work on many counts, not least its assortment of fools,
villains, innocents and also (though by no means so
numerous), its heroes.
   One of the more unforgettable sequences stars the former
best friend of the accused Betsy Kelly (who ran the nursery
school along with her husband Bob, the chief defendant). The
best friend, an articulate, vivacious woman, as so many of
the parents are, tells how her small son said he had been
slapped at Betsy and Bob's nursery school, and how when she
heard that, she knew life would never be the same. She also
relates, in passionate detail, her growing fury at Betsy, how
she wanted Betsy to plead for forgiveness, which she wouldn't
do; how all she wanted was for Betsy to beg her to bring her
son back, which Betsy also neglected to do.
   Shortly thereafter, the former friend says, she fell to
ruminating that things didn't seem right at the school. Child
welfare investigators were soon all over the place.
   This entire piece of self-revelation, whose meaning will
be lost on no viewer, is related eagerly, without awareness
of the implications. It is in short, the purest drama. The
entire hour-and-a-half of the film (to be followed by a
half-hour panel discussion) is similarly ironic, gripping,
and saturated with enough passion, betrayal, and menace to
carry several miniseries.
   Here, as in the McMartin case and similar ones,
prosecutorial zeal runs high. A few parents, maintaining
their skepticism about the charges, let it be known that they
don't believe anything happened to their children or anyone
else's. For that lack of belief, they have been punished with
hints and open threats of dire consequences.
   One such mother, who overheard her own small son's
statements being twisted into testimony of abuse by the
state's child therapist, went to the prosecutor, furious that
her child's name had been put on the list of plaintiffs. The
district attorney advised her not to go public with her
skepticism, because, he warned her, she had been named by
many children as a participant in the abuse.
   Another mother who refused to credit the abuse charges
finds that investigators are sniffing around asking questions
about her character. One of the state's therapists accuses
her of being a neglectful mother.
   There is no denying the attractiveness, innocence, and
plain confusion of some of the plaintiff parents. An attorney
-- said to be the most prominent in town -- at first
represented the chief defendant, Bob Kelly, until the good
people of Edenton spread the rumor that the lawyer's own
small son was among the abused. The attorney became an
instant and total believer. He abandoned the defense
forthwith -- and also, apparently, his capacity for
skepticism. One has the feeling that his departure was not
the worst thing in the world to happen to the defense.
   Here as everywhere else, the film maintains its polite,
even-handed stance -- but even-handedness can't diminish the
impact of the facts put before us, all of which suggest the
frenzy to convict, the fantastic nature of the charges. The
narrator reports in an entirely neutral tone one of the
children's more noteworthy accusations: The teachers had
cooked her in a microwave oven.
   The film is not without flaws, for example the somewhat
overworked motif of a peaceful Eden, where things like this
aren't supposed to happen. It is the sort of easy paradox
beloved by TV. More important, the film does all too little
to explain the exotic interrogation techniques the
prosecutors' therapists used on small children, so as to
produce accusations of abuse. But none of that much
diminishes the extraordinary power of this work.
   As this story unfolds, a defendant has no idea where the
abuse is supposed to have taken place -- all over town, the
children say -- and the defense lawyers are refused normal
access to trial materials. One is reminded of a recent
constitutional rights literacy test whose dismaying results
showed a huge proportion of those tested thought the
defendant had to prove his innocence in court. The testees
must have spent a lot of time watching child sex abuse
trials.
</TEXT>
