<HEAD>Evacuees Wax Philosophical About Florence</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Florence, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALBERTO S. FRANCO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELLE CHASSE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arthur Encalade was philosophical about
Florence, the hurricane that chased him from his home exactly 23
years after an equally rude uprooting at the hands of Hurricane
Betsy.
   As he sat among 1,200 other evacuees at Belle Chasse High School
just south of New Orleans on Friday night, the 69-year-old Encalade
said living through storms is a way of life.
   ``People live all their lives down here,'' he said. ``You hate
to leave. You go somewhere else and a tornado will take you or
something else will.
   ``It's discouraging, but what are you going to do?'' he said.
``If you're too old, you can't go far.''
   Florence was at hurricane strength Friday when the evacuees left
their low-lying homes, but lost its punch as it brushed the coast
and was downgraded to a tropical storm this morning.
   Thousands of residents of coastal areas in Mississippi, Alabama
and Florida also took refuge in shelters and homes of relatives and
friends on higher ground.
   Despite an almost casual acceptance of his situation, Encalade
said previous storms have cost him dearly.
   ``When Camille (in 1969) and Betsy came over, they cleaned us
out. I lost two houses,'' he said.
   Now Encalade lives in a trailer in Buras on the tip of the
Mississippi Delta.
   ``We've got it anchored,'' he said. ``But if the storm passes
over it's going to take it anyway. So you just lock it up and come
up here and see what happens.''
   At the school, cots were set up in the gym, with large families
grouped in classrooms. Some people brought TV sets and suitcases
with changes of clothes.
   Sitting on cots, Walter and Melodia Buras of Boothville were a
little more pragmatic than Encalade.
   ``I've been in this school three times already,'' Mrs. Buras
said. ``Once for Betsy and once for Camille. When it's a hurricane,
I'm gone.''
   They said they normally ride out weaker storms at home, but
anytime a hurricane nears shore they head for higher ground.
   Mrs. Buras said her quick departures when bad weather threatens
sometimes draw jokes from neighbors.
   ``They laugh at us when we get back, but I'd rather be safe.''
   Many shared the same outlook at St. Bernard High School east of
New Orleans, where 170 evacuees took refuge.
   ``Where we live is `God's Little Acre,''' said Ruth Gonzales,
65, of Delcroix Island. ``It's the best place to live even though
every time a storm comes through, we've got to go.''
   So why not move?
   ``If our home's destroyed, we'll make another government loan
and build again,'' she said.
</TEXT>
