<DESCRIPT>  CHILDREN; HISTORY; BOOK; TREND  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  HATRED, imprisonment, torture, starvation, violent death, war, genocide. Less
than a generation ago these were considered mature topics from which children,
especially young children, needed to be carefully shielded.;   Today, however,
that sentiment has changed. If the next generation is to do something about
the evils of the world, say some writers, educators and activists, children
need to be aware of these issues at an early age. One result is the increasing
number of picture books for preschoolers on previously taboo subjects such as
the Holocaust and Hiroshima.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  EXPLAINING THE UNSPEAKABLE
A NEW VARIETY OF CHILDREN'S BOOKS DISCUSSES THE
HORRORS OF HISTORY.
BUT ARE KIDS READY FOR IT?  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Family  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     The new crop includes:;   (check) "Let the Celebrations Begin!" (Orchard,
$14.95), a picture book for preschoolers about a young girl confined in
Bergen-Belsen concentration camp in Germany during World War II, the camp
where Anne Frank died.;   (check) "Rose Blanche" (Stewart, Tabori &amp; Chang,
$15.95), a reissued picture book, translated from the original Italian, which
tells the story of a German girl who secretly takes food to Jewish children
held in a concentration camp near her village. The girl is subsequently shot
by Nazi soldiers.;   (check) "My Hiroshima" (Viking, $12.95), a picture book
that recounts the author's memories of the atomic bombing of Hiroshima, when
she was a child.;   (check) "The Wall" (Clarion, $13.95), a picture book that
follows a young boy and his father on a visit to the Vietnam Veterans Memorial
in Washington, D.C., where they find the name of his grandfather etched on the
long black wall.;   "We're seeing a lot of books about World War II and
tremendous cataclysms coming out today, more than we've seen in a long time,"
says Ann Flowers, editor of the Boston-based Horn Book Guide, a respected
review of children's books. "Society has opened up, and people are beginning
to talk about these things more freely, and children do share more adult
concerns today.";   Although national sales figures haven't been compiled on
the most recent titles, owners of local children's bookstores say sales are
brisk.;   "Seventeen years ago we certainly had books about World War II for
readers 11 years old and up," says Harriet Zander, a former school
psychologist who owns Chanticleer bookstore in Los Gatos. "But now we're
getting requests for titles for younger and younger children." Most of the
requests, says Zander, come from teachers.;   Shula Raz, a kindergarten
teacher at Yavnev Jewish Day School in Los Gatos, has been talking about the
Holocaust with her 5-year-olds for nine years. Raised in Israel and the child
of Holocaust survivors, Raz, 44, often uses her own family's remembrances and
photographs to tell the story as simply and truthfully as she can.;   "What I
tell them depends entirely on the maturity level of the class," Raz says. "If
they ask specific questions, I will answer them. And sometimes I will show
them pictures of my sister and say, 'This girl is not alive any more. She was
killed because she was Jewish.' ";   To introduce the Holocaust, Raz says she
sometimes picks out children in her class who have black hair and brown eyes
and tells them they cannot go outside to play, or that they have to sit on
their hands all day.;   "I tell them to do something really strange, and then
I ask, 'Can you feel how children must have felt when they had to put on the
yellow star?';   "I don't dwell on it, and I don't overload them. But I answer
their questions, and I try to get them to think about how they should behave
to other people.";   Raz says she's never been approached by a parent who's
told her she's teaching the Holocaust to children who are too young. "Just the
contrary. They come in and tell me they want to hear the stories personally
that their children have been bringing home.";   Berry Kane, the father of two
children taught by Raz, says he doubts his youngsters had a "full appreciation
for the seriousness and gravity of the subject" at the age of 5 or 6. But he
approves of what they have learned in school, and he and his wife encourage
questions at home.;   "Our daughter, Emily, is 9 now, and she has begun to ask
why the Holocaust happened," Kane says. "It's hard to explain anti-Semitism
and thousands of years of history, but the simplest response I've found is to
tell her that oftentimes what people don't understand, they fear. And I tell
her, 'If you don't understand something, try and learn about it and see what's
good about it, rather than letting ignorance, or fear, or hatred govern you.'
";   Picture books in kindergarten;   Raz uses several picture books about the
Holocaust in her kindergarten classroom, including "The Children We Remember"
by Chana Byers Abells (Greenwillow, $9.95), a photographic essay of children
who died in concentration camps. During the Holocaust memorial period on the
Hebrew calendar, she also shows the children a picture book about the dropping
of the first atomic bomb.;   "Hiroshima No Pika" by Toshi Maruki (Lothrop,
$13.00) is based on the remembrances of a Japanese mother who lived through
the Hiroshima horror. The text is straightforward in its explanation that many
people and animals died in the fires. The watercolor illustrations evoke
images of intense suffering and confusion.;   "The pictures are very shocking,
but the book helps me tell kindergartners that another kind of Holocaust
happened to other people," says Raz. "And I think that's important for them to
understand." Some observers see the volume of recently published books about
the Holocaust as a natural extension of concerns that began to surface in the
late 1960s and early '70s.;   "The library profession made a strong statement
at that time that children's books should be reflecting children's worlds,"
says Betsy Hearne, editor of the Bulletin of the Center for Children's Books
at the University of Chicago.;   As a result, such issues as child abuse, AIDS
and death are included in a growing body of children's literature.;  
Ironically, the recently published "Let the Celebrations Begin!" is drawing
criticism from children's books specialists today, not because it is too
hard-hitting for a preschool audience, but because some critics say it glosses
over the Holocaust.;   Written by Margaret Wild and illustrated by Julie
Vivas, the book focuses on a time when the prisoners at Belsen were
anticipating liberation by the British. Polish women in the camp began
collecting scraps of material and buttons to make toys for a children's
party.;   Although the story is based on a brief historical account, the
occasionally lighthearted tone of the text and the lively watercolor
illustrations are both jarring and hard to believe, given the documented
suffering at the camp.;   "Why is there a compulsion in children's books to
give the Holocaust a happy ending?" writes Hazel Rochman, assistant editor of
the youth section of the American Library Association's Booklist, in the
August, 1991 issue. "In this picture book aimed at preschoolers, Belsen is a
summer camp with bunk beds, sweet secrets, homesickness and leapfrog games in
the sun.";   Rochman, a former librarian and native of South Africa who
recently edited a collection of short stories about apartheid for teen-agers,
is concerned that "Let the Celebrations Begin!" is an overly sentimentalized
story that leaves out the atrocities of the Holocaust.;   "The British troops
found 10,000 unburied bodies when they entered Belsen, and 300 people died
each day during the ensuing weeks," Rochman said in a telephone interview. "To
show children laughing and playing is to give slick comfort and a false
impression. No one had enough energy even to move. It wasn't a party.";   Does
this kind of criticism mean that children's authors should steer clear of
concentration-camp stories? No, says the Bulletin's Betsy Hearne. What's
important is whether the material remains true to the events that are depicted
and how adults share controversial books with children.;   And there can be
other problems. Hearne, for example, criticizes "Rose Blanche," which looks
like a picture book but is more appropriate for older readers. The
illustrations by Roberto Innocenti border on the surreal, and at least one
page, which shows a young boy being taken prisoner by Nazi soldiers, derives
from a famous wartime photograph.;   Are children ready?;   "There are so many
references like that (to the well-known photograph) that children wouldn't
understand," Hearne says. "And I think the ending is pretty ambiguous, too.
Kids really wouldn't have a clue what was happening.";   Given these and other
artistic problems, perhaps the fundamental question that needs to be asked is:
Are children of preschool age really equipped to understand and respond in a
constructive way to the violence and hatred that surround the Holocaust?;  
"My hunch is that at about the age of 10 or 11, kids would begin to get a much
better grasp on the Holocaust," says Robin Keller, a Berkeley psychotherapist
who has studied more than 140 Bay Area adults who are children of Holocaust
survivors.;   "But so much depends on the way in which information about the
Holocaust is communicated," she adds. "Some families have told their children
about the Holocaust in a very guilt-inducing way, and children exposed to that
kind of environment have later tended to distance themselves from their
families.;   "On the other hand, when information about the Holocaust has been
related in an educational or historical way, then it hasn't seemed to have a
negative effect. If there's been an openness to questions in a family, there's
much more interest in and acceptance of the Holocaust.";   Writing before they
die; The current interest in children's books about the Holocaust and other
war-related events can be attributed to several factors, say experts such as
the Horn Book's Flowers. For one thing, there are many authors who have lived
quietly with their memories for many years and now want to get their stories
into print before they die.;   "I think some things are just too deep to be
talked about for quite a while for the people who've lived through them,"
Flowers says. "It often takes a long time for honest feelings to be expressed
in artistic ways, particularly in fine literature.";   In fact, some new books
about World War II for older readers are adding new dimensions to the genre,
says ALA Booklist's Rochman. "The Man From the Other Side," a story about a
young boy and his father who help rescue Jews in the Warsaw ghetto, recently
translated from the Hebrew by Hilel Halkin, is breaking new ground in several
ways, she says.;   "For the first time that I can remember in a young-adult
book, the Jews aren't presented as an amorphous mass of victims and heroes,"
Rochman notes. "Some are brave and some are traitors. There's a real range of
individuals.;   "It's an exciting story, and it's also a story about moral
choice."  </TEXT>
