<HEADLINE>  TWO SHARE LEAD -- IT'S JUST PAR FOR THE COURSE  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Chart attached to the end of this article  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Yes. After two rounds at Colonial Country Club, no players are under par.
Bradley, 40, the all-time leading money-winner on the LPGA Tour, shares the
second-round lead at even-par 142 with Joan Pitcock, who has not won in four
years on the tour.;    Pitcock shot a 1-over 72 and Bradley a 73 on Friday.;  
 They are one shot ahead of Alice Ritzman and Amy Alcott, the 1980 U.S.
Women's Open champion who shot a 68 Friday.;    Defending champion Betsy King
barely made the cut, 10 shots behind, with a 7-over-par 78.;    "I am a little
surprised," Bradley said. "There's always a player or two or three that makes
liars of tough conditions and tough putting. But I guess we all have been kept
at bay with the wind, heat and putting surfaces.";    "It was a long day. Five
hours is an awful long time to be out there. Golf is a game of momentum, and
for 16 holes we were twiddling our thumbs out there. I thought a 73 was pretty
good, to tell the truth.";    Pitcock, 23, said she was surprised to be tied
for the lead.;    "It's different as a professional," she said. "You have to
worry about making cuts, and as an amateur you could freewheel it. I'm
surprised to be here.";    LPGA champion Meg Mallon shot a 75 and was in a
group of five at 145 that included former champion JoAnne Carner.;    King was
disenchanted with her playing partners, the greens and the course as she saw
her bid for a third consecutive Open title dim.;    "It's been a strange week,
and obviously I would like to have played better," said King, who made it
clear she didn't like historic Colonial and its sun-baked, spike-marked bent
grass greens.;    "I can't say it's one of my favorite courses," King said.
"I'd be lying if I said I wasn't disappointed in the conditions.";    King
wiped away tears several times during her interview, then became so emotional
she left the press room through a back curtain.;    She posted two double
bogeys and a triple bogey Friday. Twice she miscalculated iron shots and found
the water.;    "It was hard to judge out there, a big guessing game," she
said. "It takes more than talent to hit a shot.";    Earlier in the week, she
had complained about pin placements, the watering of greens during the round,
and being paired with amateur Sandrine Mendiburu of France.;      U.S. Open;
